<fact>
    <statement>
        <p>
            In order for a nonempty sub<em>set</em> <m>S</m> of a vector space <m>V</m> to be a sub<em>space</em>, we must first check that the operations <m>S</m>
            inherits from <m>V</m> are defined on <m>S</m>.
            <aside>
                <p>Recall that we are using the convention that an "operation on <m>S</m>" must have a codomain of <m>S</m>.</p>
            </aside>
            In other words, we need to check two things:  
        </p>
            <ul>
            <li>
                <p>
                The set is <term>closed under addition</term><idx><h>vector space</h></idx><idx>closed under addition</idx>: for any <m>\vec{u},\vec{v} \in S</m>, the sum <m>\vec{u}+\vec{v}</m> is also in <m>S</m>.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                The set is <term>closed under scalar multiplication</term><idx><h>vector space</h></idx><idx>closed under scalar multiplication</idx>: for any <m>\vec{u} \in S</m> and scalar <m>c \in \IR</m>, the product <m>c\vec{u}</m> is also in <m>S</m>.
                </p>
            </li>
            </ul>
        <p>Once we have verified the operations are closed and thus well-defined on <m>S</m>, we get the eight vector space properties for free.</p>
            <ul><li>
                <p>
                    Six of the eight (e.g. commutativity) propertieshold directly since they hold in <m>V</m>.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    Since <m>0 \in \IR</m> and <m>S</m> is closed under scalar multiplication, we see <m>\vec{0}=0\odot \vec{v}</m> is in <m>S</m> for 
                    any <m>\vec{v} \in S</m>.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    Since <m>-1 \in \IR</m> and <m>S</m> is closed under scalar multiplication, we see <m>-\vec{v}=-1\odot \vec{v}</m> is in <m>S</m> for 
                    any <m>\vec{v} \in S</m>.
                </p>
            </li></ul>
    </statement>
</fact>

